Origin and derivation status
----------------------------

Andes began as a Rust reimplementation of MS-GF+ and we acknowledge that
heritage explicitly. The project is being made independent of MS-GF+ in
stages, and this NOTICE tracks the honest current status:

  * Scoring engine (code) — INDEPENDENT. The patented generating-function
    code has been removed (ranking uses an empirical RawScore calibration),
    and the rank/intensity scoring has been clean-room reimplemented from the
    published intensity-rank log-likelihood idea (Frank 2005; Kim et al.) —
    not ported line-by-line.

  * Trained statistical models (resources/ionstat/models.parquet) — STILL
    DERIVED. These rank/error/noise tables are, for now, derived from
    MS-GF+'s released `.param` files. They are being retrained from public
    and reanalysed data via the bundled `train` engine; until every shipped
    model is independently trained, Andes remains a derivative work for
    licensing purposes.

Because MS-GF+-derived models are still bundled, Andes is distributed under
the same UC Regents non-commercial license terms as upstream (see ./LICENSE);
no broader rights are granted by the Andes authors, and commercial use
requires a separate license from UC San Diego's Technology Transfer Office.
When all bundled models are independently trained, the Andes authors intend
to relicense the project under permissive terms; this NOTICE will be updated
at that point.

The Rust architecture, performance work, parallel search pipeline, training
engine, and own-trained models contributed by the Andes authors are original
work.

This NOTICE file must be preserved in all distributions, in source or
